{"key":"post-9533564","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9533564</id>\n<content>You're going to spend more than the 20 cents a dish costs to clean and re-sterilize it, especially if you count your own time as money.&amp;nbsp; Then, you have to think about how you're going to keep it sterile until you get it out of the pc.&amp;nbsp; You'll want a sterilizer so it can pull a vacuum until you open it.&amp;nbsp; A pc with a weight will allow contaminants in as soon as the pressure reaches zero.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've often heard people say it's bad for the environment to toss plastic dishes out.&amp;nbsp; However, for some reason they don't think it's bad for the environment to dump soap down the drain and/or use electricity from coal to run a sterilizer. &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:shrug:&quot; title=&quot;:shrug:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Pre-sterilized sleeves of Petri dishes should be available in every city with a hospital district.&amp;nbsp; Look up laboratory supplies in the phone book.&amp;nbsp; I get mine locally.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9533568</next>\n<prev>9533543</prev>\n<first>9532842</first>\n<last>9539131</last>\n<when>1230946817</when>\n<utime>01/03/09 03:40 AM</utime>\n</post>"}